config.text: ﻿Welcome to the NC Shellfish Aquaculture Siting Tool!

﻿This map application was produced for data visualization purposes to assist the public in accessing publicly available datasets and streamline the shellfish bottom lease site selection process. The tool is maintained by the University of North Carolina Wilmington (UNCW) and provides information on the coastal conditions for North Carolina as of August 2025. The public data in the NC Shellfish Aquaculture Siting Tool is provided by multiple agencies, and UNCW cannot guarantee the quality, accuracy, or collection methods of the data. The NC Shellfish Aquaculture Siting Tool should only be used as a reference. It should not be taken as a fact of current conditions and is not a substitute for site verification. If you have any questions, please contact Troy Alphin (alphint@uncw.edu).

parameters.description: User drawn area of interest. Use the tool to draw your area of interest where you want to extract data.

parameters.name: Feature_Format
parameters.description:
Specifies the format of the output features. The format should be specified as follows: • Name or format - Short Name - extension (if any)The hyphens are required and there must be one space before and after the hyphen. 
For example: 
• File Geodatabase - GDB - .gdb
• Shapefile - SHP - .shp
• Autodesk AutoCAD - DXF_R2007 - .dxf
• Autodesk AutoCAD - DWG_R2007 - .dwg
• Bentley Microstation Design (V8) - DGN_V8 - .dgn
The list of short names supported includes DGN_V8, DWG_R14, DWG_R2000, DWG_R2004, DWG_R2005, DWG_R2007, DWG_R2010, DXF_R14, DXF_R2000, DXF_R2004, DXF_R2005, DXF_R2007, and DXF_R2010.

parameters.name: Raster_Format
parameters.description:
Specifies the format of the output raster datasets. The format should be specified as follows:• Name of format - Short Name - extension (if any)The hyphens are required and there must be one space before and after the hyphen.
For example:
• Esri GRID - GRID
•File Geodatabase - GDB - .gdb
• ERDAS IMAGINE - IMG - .img
• Tagged Image File Format - TIFF - .tif
• Portable Network Graphics - PNG - .png
• Graphic Interchange Format - GIF - .gif
• Joint Photographics Experts Group - JPEG - .jpg
• Joint Photographics Experts Group - JPEG - .jp2
• Bitmap - BMP - .bmpSome of the above raster formats have limitations and not all data can be converted to the format.

config.text: ﻿Welcome to the NC Shellfish Aquaculture Siting Tool!

﻿This map application was produced for data visualization purposes to assist the public in accessing publicly available datasets and streamline the shellfish bottom lease site selection process. The tool is maintained by the University of North Carolina Wilmington (UNCW) and provides information on the coastal conditions for North Carolina as of August 2024. The public data in the NC Shellfish Aquaculture Siting Tool is provided by multiple agencies, and UNCW cannot guarantee the quality, accuracy, or collection methods of the data. The NC Shellfish Aquaculture Siting Tool should only be used as a reference. It should not be taken as a fact of current conditions and is not a substitute for site verification. If you have any questions, please contact Troy Alphin (alphint@uncw.edu).

The NC Shellfish Aquaculture Siting Tool serves as an interactive-support mapping tool of the North Carolina coastline that helps to streamline the leasing process for the NC shellfish aquaculture industry, potential shellfish growers, and existing shellfish growers. The map tool is a central reference location for several key layers of data related to shellfish growth including bottom type, depth soundings, current shellfish leases, shellfish growing area classifications, boat access areas, and surrounding land use. The tool is designed to provide information to help potential shellfish growers determine site feasibility and help them identify potential risks and long-term suitability for potential areas. ﻿

config.text: Your feedback shapes the future of this tool, share your thoughts!

We'd love to hear your thoughts on your experience! Your feedback helps us improve and tailer this tool to better meet your needs. widget_337.label: help us make this tool better, window text 2

config.text: Help us make this tool even better!!
We'd love to hear your thoughts on your experience! Your feedback helps us improve and tailer this tool to better meet your needs.

Web Experience Tutorial

Follow this guided tutorial to explore the app’s features and learn how to use its tools.

Primary Experience Interface

Explore the "About the tool..." bar for additional project and contact information.

Navigate to the Menu Bar in the top right corner for external links.

Primary Experience Interface

Explore the "Layers Widget" to view the map’s layers and turn them on or off to customize what you see. Use the "Legend Widget" (below the "Layers Widget") to understand what the map's colors and symbols represent for each layer.

Primary Experience Interface

Navigate to the "Basemap Tool" to change the background map to one that best fits your needs. Use the "Search Tool" (top left corner) to find locations by address or place name. Navigate the map by using your mouse scroll wheel or the + / – buttons (bottom right corner) on the map to zoom in and out.

Primary Experience Interface

Move and expand the "Layers Widget" and "Legend Widget" to your preference. You can also move layers up or down to control which layers appear on top. Click on a feature on the map to view more information about it.

Toolbar Widgets: Add Data

Use the Add Data Tool (first button in the toolbar) to upload your own data layers from ArcGIS content, a URL, or local storage (shapefile, CSV, KML, GeoJSON, GPX). This example uses a KML file exported from Google Earth. After selecting a file, click done. Then click the Actions icon to the right of your new layer's name to Add to the Map.

Toolbar Widgets: Draw

Use the Draw Tool (second button in the toolbar) to create points, lines, and shapes on the map. This example draws a polygon and displays the area (in acres) and perimeter (in feet). Before drawing, turn on "Show area measurement" and/or "Show perimeter measurement" to collect information in your desired units. Choose from a variety of colors and styles and customize the settings.

altTextExpression.name: User selects the Draw a Point option within the Draw Tool to create points on the map and selects Show Location Measurement to include the points coordinates. The user also uses the Draw a Polyline option to create lines with length measurements enabled.

parts.exp: "User selects the Draw a Point option within the Draw Tool to create points on the map and selects Show Location Measurement to include the points coordinates. The user also uses the Draw a Polyline option to create lines with length measurements enabled."

config.text:
Toolbar Widgets: Draw

Select "Draw a Point" within the Draw Tool to create points on the map. Select from a variety of different styles by using the "Source" drop-down menu. Turn on "Show location measurement" to display the coordinates of the point(s) in Decimal Degrees or Degrees Minutes Seconds units. You can also create lines with length measurements using the "Draw a Polyline" drawing mode.

altTextExpression.name: User opens the Map XY widget, enters a set of coordinates, and the map zooms to the specified location with a marker placed on it

parts.exp: "User opens the Map XY widget, enters a set of coordinates, and the map zooms to the specified location with a marker placed on it"

config.text:
Toolbar Widgets: Map XY

Use the Map XY Tool (third button in the toolbar) to find a point location by using coordinates in latitude and longitude (here is an example in decimal degrees (DD) format: 34.400881°‎N, 077.597315°‎W) or an address. Alternatively, use the "Add Point" option next to "Enter Coordinates/Address", to retrieve the coordinates and address of a point. Use the Copy tool to copy the coordinates and/or address to your clipboard. You can also add or change coordinate conversions.

altTextExpression.name: User opens the Select widget, chooses which data layers to select data from, and then draws an area of interest around desired data to highlight on the map, zoom or pan to the data, and/or view the data in the table.

parts.exp: "User opens the Select widget, chooses which data layers to select data from, and then draws an area of interest around desired data to highlight on the map, zoom or pan to the data, and/or view the data in the table. "

config.text:
Toolbar Widgets: Select

Use the Select Tool (fourth button in the toolbar) to select features from specified data layers using interactive map selection. Select desired data from layer's list and draw by using either select by rectangle, circle, point, lasso, or line; draw your shape accordingly around your desired data. With data selected, use the "Actions" button next to the layer's name to zoom or pan to the data, open and view in the table at the bottom of the map, and/or export the data to a JSON, GeoJSON, CSV, or an Item.
SHELLFISH MARICULTURE PROPEL

Propel offers participants in the shellfish mariculture industry a business incubator curriculum and process to assist growers through the stages of business launch and growth. This fully online business training series presents new growers with concepts and challenges of business ownership unique to shellfish growers. This program also provides resources that can be used after the course has been completed.


*see Menu bar in top right corner for website link*


Contact cie@uncw.edu for more information and to enroll in this free course.


Funding provided in part by NOAA Sea Grant Award NOAA-OAR-SG-2020-2006331
FREE Online asynchronous course

parts.exp: "User opens the Map XY widget, enters a set of coordinates, and the map zooms to the specified location with a marker placed on it"

config.text:
Toolbar Widgets: Extract Data

Use the Extract Data Tool (fifth button in the toolbar) to interactively extract data from layers on the map into a .zip file by drawing an area of interest using a polygon, rectangle, or circle. Select from menu which layers you would like to extract data from. Use the "Draw Input Features" button to draw an area of interest on the map where you want to extract data. Specify the Feature and Raster Formats for exported data. Click "Run", then download your zipped data file by navigating to the "History" tab, selecting "View Details", and clicking on the ".zip" file name; this will automatically download the zipped file to your device.

Toolbar Widgets: Survey

Use the Survey Tool (sixth button in the toolbar) to provide optional and anonymous feedback on the usability of the tool. This survey was created using ArcGIS Survey123 and all responses will only be used for informational purposes to improve the tool. Feel free to submit your contact information if you would like to be contacted. Ensure you click "Submit" to have your responses recorded.

Toolbar Widgets: Print

Use the Print Tool (seventh button in the toolbar) to print your web map and any scene you draw or create. Open the "Advanced" drop down menu to select different settings to customize your exported map. Customizable settings include choosing the map's extent (view), including/excluding a legend and/or north arrow, specifying the map scale units (miles, kilometers, meters or feet), and the print quality (higher DPI = better output resolution of map)﻿. Make sure to download your "Map" from the "Results" tab.
NC BLUE ECONOMY ASSETS MAP

The UNCW Center for Innovation and Entrepreneurship has mapped out Blue Economy businesses, startups, and other assets in North Carolina as part of their All Blue program. To classify the various assets, there are 10 different sectors of the Blue Economy plotted in addition to NC Sea Grant office locations and offshore wind leases underway with Carolina Long Bay, Duke Energy, and Kitty Hawk Wind. The goal of this ongoing project is to visually display data that represents the Blue Economy Assets in North Carolina, provide a resource and database for entrepreneur support organizations and/or for those interested in the Blue Economy, and inspire residents of North Carolina to expand their efforts, connections, and businesses to revolve around the Blue Economy.


*see Menu bar in top right corner for website link*


Contact cie@uncw.edu for more information OR add your Business by stating your businesses name, founder or director, website and the business address.
